▁ (\ref{a})▁ can▁ be▁ used▁ to▁ roughly▁ predict▁ the▁ average▁ ,▁ or▁ characteristic▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ $v$▁ $A^{\frac{1}{2}}$▁ which▁ ,▁ according▁ to▁ (\ref{a})▁ is▁ relevant▁ for▁ the▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ ,▁ varies▁ across▁ the▁ periodic▁ table▁ in▁ the▁ range▁ of▁ about▁ ,▁ with▁ an▁ average▁ value▁ of▁ According▁ to▁ (\ref{a})▁ ,▁ the▁ corresponding▁ $v$▁ is▁ $v\approx 4,513\frac{\rm m}{\rm s}$▁ This▁ is▁ in▁ \%▁ agreement▁ with▁ ,▁ $\frac{\rm m}{\rm s}$▁ ,▁ the▁ average▁ over▁ all▁ elemental▁ solids▁ and▁ in▁ \%▁ agreement▁ with▁ ,▁ $\frac{\rm m}{\rm s}$▁ ,▁ the▁ average▁ over▁ all▁ solids▁ in▁ \ref{all}▁ We▁ have▁ included▁ the▁ experimental▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ of▁ room▁ temperature▁ liquids▁ in▁ \ref{all}▁ ,▁ with▁ typical▁ $v$▁ in▁ the▁ range▁ ,▁ ,▁ $\frac{\rm m}{\rm s}$▁ $v$▁ in▁ high-temperature▁ liquid▁ such▁ as▁ ,▁ ,▁ ,▁ and▁ extends▁ to▁ higher▁ values▁ in▁ the▁ range▁ ,▁ ,▁ $\frac{\rm m}{\rm s}$▁ \cite{metals}▁ Similarly▁ to▁ solids▁ ,▁ $v$▁ in▁ liquids▁ satisfy▁ the▁ bound▁ $v_u$▁ We▁ note▁ that▁ our▁ evaluation▁ of▁ $v$▁ and▁ $v_u$▁ applies▁ to▁ liquids▁ with▁ states▁ \cite{f2}▁ ,▁ where▁ molecular▁ dynamics▁ includes▁ solid▁ like▁ oscillatory▁ components▁ \cite{frenkel}▁ and▁ where▁ $v$▁ is▁ set▁ by▁ the▁ elastic▁ moduli▁ as▁ in▁ solids▁ ,▁ albeit▁ taken▁ at▁ their▁ high▁ frequency▁ (short-time)▁ values▁ \cite{frenkel,boon}▁ On▁ the▁ other▁ hand▁ ,▁ at▁ high▁ temperature▁ and/or▁ density▁ ,▁ states▁ are▁ lost▁ and▁ (\ref{rydberg})▁ and▁ (\ref{bohr})▁ and▁ our▁ derivation▁ of▁ $v$▁ do▁ not▁ apply▁ In▁ this▁ regime▁ ,▁ the▁ moduli▁ are▁ related▁ to▁ the▁ kinetic▁ energy▁ of▁ molecules▁ rather▁ than▁ interactions▁ and▁ on▁ in▁ energy▁ ,▁ and▁ $v$▁ starts▁ to▁ increase▁ with▁ temperature▁ and▁ loses▁ its▁ universality▁ Above▁ the▁ line▁ \cite{f1,f2,f3}▁ ,▁ formal▁ is▁ in▁ the▁ qualitative▁ change▁ of▁ molecular▁ dynamics▁ from▁ combined▁ oscillatory▁ and▁ diff▁ us▁ to▁ purely▁ diff▁ us▁ ,▁ $v$▁ is▁ equal▁ to▁ the▁ thermal▁ speed▁ of▁ molecules▁ as▁ in▁ as▁ With▁ regard▁ to▁ liquids▁ ,▁ we▁ note▁ that▁ an▁ expression▁ similar▁ to▁ (\ref{v01})▁ was▁ earlier▁ obtained▁ by▁ evaluating▁ the▁ elastic▁ modulus▁ using▁ the▁ liquid▁ state▁ theory▁ and▁ applied▁ to▁ liquid▁ \cite{gitis}▁ The▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ can▁ also▁ be▁ evaluated▁ in▁ the▁ theory▁ of▁ using▁ the▁ on▁ plasma▁ frequency▁ and▁ subsequently▁ accounting▁ for▁ the▁ conduction▁ electrons▁ screening▁ This▁ results▁ in▁ the▁ relation▁ $v\propto\left(\frac{m_e}{m}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}v_{\rm F}$▁ ,▁ where▁ $v_{\rm F}$▁ is▁ the▁ Fermi▁ velocity▁ \cite{ashcroft}▁ ,▁ and▁ hence▁ $v\propto\frac{1}{A^\frac{1}{2}}$▁ as▁ in▁ (\ref{a})▁ (the factor $\left(\frac{m_e}{m}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}$ also appears in the ratio of sound to melting velocity \cite{hartnoll1})▁ These▁ and▁ other▁ relations▁ derived▁ for▁ the▁ liquid▁ state▁ give▁ fairly▁ good▁ account▁ of▁ the▁ experimental▁ sound▁ velocity▁ in▁ liquid▁ \cite{gitis,metals}▁ We▁ make▁ three▁ further▁ remarks▁ about▁ the▁ calculated▁ $v$▁ and▁ its▁ bound▁ First▁ ,▁ this▁ derivation▁ involves▁ approximations▁ as▁ mentioned▁ earlier▁ The▁ approximations▁ may▁ affect▁ the▁ numerical▁ factor▁ in▁ (\ref{v00})▁ and▁ (\ref{v3})▁ the▁ same▁ time▁ ,▁ the▁ characteristic▁ scale▁ of▁ $v$▁ in▁ (\ref{v00})▁ and▁ its▁ upper▁ bound▁ (\ref{v3})▁ is▁ set▁ by▁ fundamental▁ constants▁ Second▁ ,▁ (\ref{rydberg})▁ as▁ well▁ as▁ (\ref{bohr})▁ (\ref{ratio})▁ used▁ in▁ the▁ second▁ derivation▁ of▁ $v$▁ assume▁ valence▁ electrons▁ directly▁ involved▁ in▁ on▁ in▁ and▁ hence▁ strongly▁ on▁ systems▁ ,▁ including▁ metallic▁ ,▁ oval▁ and▁ on▁ solids▁ Although▁ on▁ in▁ in▁ weakly▁ on▁ solids▁ such▁ as▁ ,▁ molecular▁ and▁ hydrogen▁ on▁ solids▁ is▁ also▁ electromagnetic▁ in▁ origin▁ ,▁ weak▁ dipole▁ and▁ an▁ Waals▁ interactions▁ result▁ in▁ smaller▁ $E$▁ \cite{vadim1}▁ and▁ smaller▁ $v$▁ as▁ result▁ Therefore▁ ,▁ the▁ upper▁ bound▁ $v_u$▁ applies▁ to▁ weakly▁ on▁ systems▁ to▁ We▁ note▁ here▁ that▁ our▁ evaluation▁ does▁ not▁ directly▁ distinguish▁ betwee