▁ Our▁ upper▁ bound▁ (\ref{v3})▁ does▁ not▁ account▁ for▁ the▁ contribution▁ to▁ the▁ system▁ energy▁ as▁ mentioned▁ earlier▁ including▁ the▁ pressure▁ effect▁ would▁ increase▁ $v_u$▁ considerably▁ at▁ pressures▁ in▁ \ref{abinitio}▁ Despite▁ this▁ ,▁ the▁ calculated▁ $v$▁ remains▁ below▁ $v_u$▁ in▁ wide▁ pressure▁ range▁ and▁ starts▁ increasing▁ above▁ $v_u$▁ only▁ above▁ very▁ high▁ pressure▁ of▁ about▁ In▁ this▁ regard▁ ,▁ we▁ note▁ that▁ hydrogen▁ is▁ unique▁ element▁ with▁ core▁ electrons▁ This▁ results▁ in▁ the▁ absence▁ of▁ strong▁ repulsive▁ contributions▁ to▁ the▁ inter▁ atomic▁ interaction▁ as▁ compared▁ with▁ heavier▁ elements▁ and▁ ,▁ consequently▁ ,▁ weaker▁ pressure▁ dependence▁ of▁ elastic▁ moduli▁ and▁ the▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ \cite{vadim2}▁ We▁ also▁ note▁ that▁ sharper▁ change▁ of▁ $v$▁ at▁ lower▁ pressure▁ in▁ \ref{abinitio}▁ is▁ related▁ to▁ approaching▁ the▁ limit▁ of▁ dynamical▁ stability▁ of▁ the▁ $I4_1/amd$▁ structure▁ around▁ We▁ make▁ three▁ remarks▁ related▁ to▁ previous▁ work▁ It▁ was▁ noted▁ that▁ thermal▁ diff▁ us▁ it▁ of▁ in▁ at▁ or▁ does▁ not▁ fall▁ below▁ threshold▁ value▁ given▁ by▁ the▁ product▁ of▁ $v^2$▁ and▁ the▁ Planckian▁ time▁ \cite{behnia}▁ Later▁ work▁ linked▁ the▁ upper▁ bound▁ on▁ the▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ to▁ the▁ in▁ velocity▁ related▁ to▁ in▁ temperature▁ and▁ Linde▁ mann▁ criterion▁ \cite{hartnoll1}▁ Finally▁ ,▁ the▁ upper▁ bound▁ of▁ the▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ for▁ hadronic▁ matter▁ was▁ conjectured▁ as▁ $\frac{c}{\sqrt{3}}$▁ and▁ discussed▁ (see, e.g., Ref. \cite{hadronic})▁ for▁ review▁ Comparing▁ this▁ bound▁ with▁ (\ref{v0})▁ ,▁ we▁ that▁ our▁ bound▁ is▁ smaller▁ to▁ small▁ coupling▁ constant▁ $\alpha$▁ and▁ the▁ electron▁ to▁ proton▁ mass▁ ratio▁ In▁ hadronic▁ matter▁ with▁ strong▁ coupling▁ and▁ particles▁ with▁ the▁ same▁ or▁ similar▁ masses▁ ,▁ these▁ factors▁ become▁ on▁ the▁ order▁ of▁ ,▁ in▁ which▁ case▁ our▁ $\frac{v_u}{c}$▁ in▁ (\ref{v0})▁ becomes▁ closer▁ to▁ the▁ conjectured▁ limit▁ \cite{hadronic}▁ Our▁ upper▁ bound▁ for▁ $v$▁ is▁ consistent▁ with▁ the▁ recent▁ discussion▁ of▁ Planckian▁ relax▁ ation▁ time▁ ,▁ or▁ Planckian▁ dissipation▁ ,▁ used▁ to▁ explain▁ the▁ bounds▁ on▁ physical▁ properties▁ and▁ universal▁ behaviour▁ of▁ quasi▁ particles▁ in▁ range▁ of▁ systems▁ An▁ uncertainty▁ relation▁ applied▁ to▁ particle▁ or▁ quasi▁ particle▁ with▁ thermal▁ energy▁ $k_{\rm B}T$▁ ,▁ puts▁ bound▁ for▁ the▁ Planckian▁ relax▁ ation▁ time▁ as▁ $\tau_\hbar>\frac{\hbar}{k_{\rm B}T}$▁ \cite{zaanen3,hartnoll,zaanen2}▁ This▁ notably▁ gives▁ {\it lower}▁ bound▁ for▁ characteristic▁ time▁ of▁ local▁ relax▁ ation▁ process▁ ,▁ which▁ ,▁ in▁ turn▁ ,▁ results▁ in▁ lower▁ bounds▁ for▁ transport▁ properties▁ such▁ as▁ is▁ it▁ \cite{kss,zaanen3,hartnoll,zaanen2,spin,zaanen1}▁ because▁ is▁ it▁ is▁ proportional▁ to▁ relax▁ ation▁ time▁ Important▁ ,▁ the▁ same▁ relation▁ for▁ $\tau_\hbar$▁ gives▁ the▁ {\it upper}▁ bound▁ for▁ the▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ in▁ solids▁ ,▁ $v$▁ ,▁ because▁ $v$▁ is▁ inversely▁ proportional▁ to▁ the▁ time▁ scale▁ Indeed▁ ,▁ $v$▁ in▁ (\ref{v001})▁ can▁ be▁ equivalently▁ written▁ as▁ $v=\frac{a}{\tau_{\rm D}}$▁ ,▁ where▁ $\tau_{\rm D}$▁ is▁ the▁ by▁ ratio▁ period▁ $\tau_{\rm D}$▁ is▁ on▁ the▁ order▁ of▁ the▁ shortest▁ elementary▁ period▁ of▁ atomic▁ ratio▁ ,▁ $\tau_0$▁ Its▁ lower▁ bound▁ follows▁ from▁ $\tau_0>\frac{\hbar}{k_{\rm B}T}$▁ as▁ discussed▁ above▁ Combining▁ this▁ with▁ $v=\frac{a}{\tau_0}$▁ gives▁ $v<a\frac{k_{\rm B}T}{\hbar}$▁ This▁ defines▁ an▁ upper▁ bound▁ which▁ varies▁ with▁ temperature▁ and▁ increases▁ to▁ its▁ maximal▁ value▁ at▁ temperature▁ comparable▁ to▁ the▁ in▁ temperature▁ $T_m$▁ where▁ solids▁ cease▁ to▁ exist▁ Hence▁ ,▁ the▁ largest▁ $v$▁ is▁ given▁ by▁ $v<a\frac{k_{\rm B}T_m}{\hbar}$▁ ,▁ consistent▁ with▁ the▁ result▁ in▁ \cite{hartnoll1}▁ derived▁ using▁ different▁ approach▁ based▁ on▁ the▁ Linde▁ mann▁ criterion▁ of▁ in▁ Taking▁ $a\approx 1$▁ and▁ characteristic▁ value▁ of▁ $T_m$▁ of▁ $10^3$▁ gives▁ the▁ upper▁ bound▁ for▁ $v$▁ on▁ the▁ order▁ of▁ $10^{4}$▁ This▁ is▁ consistent▁ with▁ the▁ order▁ of▁ $v_u$▁ in▁ (\ref{v3})▁ ,▁ although▁ (\ref{v3})▁ gives▁ more▁ precise▁ bound▁ in▁ terms▁ of▁ fundamental▁ constants▁ As▁ discussed▁ above▁ ,▁ $v$▁ features▁ in▁ several▁ thermodynamic▁ properties▁ of▁ solids▁ For▁ example▁ ,▁ the▁ temperature▁ entropy▁ and▁ heat▁ capacity▁ volume▁ are▁ $\frac{S}{V}=\frac{2\pi^2}{15(\hbar u)^3}T^3$▁ and▁ $\frac{C}{V}=\frac{2\pi^2}{5(\hbar u)^3}T^3$▁ ,▁ where▁ $u$▁ is▁ the▁ average▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ and▁ $k_{\rm B}=1$▁ \cite{landau}▁ Hence▁ ,▁ the▁ upper▁ bound▁ for▁ $u$▁ gives▁ the▁ smallest▁ possible▁ entropy▁ and▁ heat▁ capacity▁ at▁ given▁ temperature▁ \section{Materials and Methods}▁ We▁ have▁ performed▁ density▁ functional▁ theory▁ calculations▁ using▁ the▁ {\sc castep}▁ package▁ \cite{castep}▁ ,▁ with▁ the▁ Burke▁ of▁ (PBE)▁ exchange▁ correlation▁ functional▁ \cite{pbe}▁ ,▁ an▁ energy▁ cutoff▁ of▁ $1200$▁ \,▁ and▁ $\mathbf{k}$▁ point▁ grid▁ of▁ spacing▁ $2\pi\times0.025$▁ \,▁ $^{-1}$▁ to▁ sample▁ the▁ electronic▁ in▁ one▁ We▁ have▁ relaxed▁ the▁ cell▁ parameters▁ and▁ internal▁ coordinates▁ to▁ obtain▁ pressure▁ to▁ within▁ $10^{-4}$▁ of▁ the▁ target▁ pressure▁ and▁ forces▁ smaller▁ than▁ $10^{-5}$▁ \,▁ We▁ have▁ then▁ calculated▁ the▁ phonon▁ spectrum▁ using▁ the▁ finite▁ difference▁ method▁ \cite{fd_martin}▁ in▁ conjunction▁ with▁ nondiagonal▁ super▁ cells▁ \cite{nondiagonal}▁ with▁ $4\times4\times4$▁ coarse▁ $\mathbf{q}$▁ point▁ grid▁ to▁ sample▁ the▁ vibrational▁ in▁ one▁ We▁ have▁ used▁ Fourier▁ interpolation▁ to▁ calculate▁ the▁ phonon▁ frequencies▁ at▁ $\mathbf{q}$▁ vectors▁ close▁ to▁ the▁ $\Gamma$▁ point▁ and▁ then▁ used▁ finite▁ differences▁ to▁ calculate▁ the▁ corresponding▁ speed▁ of▁ sound▁ \section{Conclusions}▁ We▁ conclude▁ by▁ returning▁ to▁ dimensionless▁ fundamental▁ physical▁ constants▁ Rewriting▁ (\ref{v3})▁ as▁ \begin{equation}
\frac{v_u}{c}=\alpha\left(\frac{m_e}{2m_p}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}},
\label{v4}
\end{equation}
